posts.name: Brian Wagg
posts.cooked:
SOLIDWORKS:

apply for your free team license here

I just started filling out the form, but am confused by the Age Declaration portion of it.

It states:

By agreeing, you represent to DS that all team members are at least eighteen (18) years old and capable of entering into a legally binding agreement or, if any of your teammates are under eighteen (18) years old, that you provided DS with an adequate parental authorization to do so.

This suggests to me that the person filling out the form, who is a mentor/”leader”, is expected to either give authorization on behalf of their students (not something any mentor/coach is able to do) or get some form of authorization (in writing) from each team member on the team under the age of 18 that will be using Dassault Systèmes software (I do not see any place to download and reupload signed forms/waivers).

Would appreciate any guidance you can here. Thanks!

Thank you for catching that! This is a mistake. The statement should say:

By agreeing, you represent to DS that all team members using cloud-based products are at least eighteen (18) years old and capable of entering into a legally binding agreement or, if any of your teammates are under eighteen (18) years old, that you provided DS with an adequate parental authorization to do so.

SOLIDWORKS desktop by itself does not connect to the internet, is not tied to your name, and has no reason for an age limitation.

The cloud products, however, do require parental consent for users under 18 because they need to create named user accounts to log in. The parental authorization form and the location to submit it appears when you choose an offering that uses cloud services.

I have contacted the appropriate team to get this updated. Thank you again for bringing this to our attention!

posts.name: Andrew Torrance
posts.cooked:
This process of parental consent / submitting the spreadsheet with names of all the students is a major turn-off for any if solidworks’ online services, such as 3D Experience.

Onshape does not require this, teams can much more easily create accounts for their students and invite them to the team.

Thank you for this feedback. I’ve reported this concern to the appropriate teams to see about the possibility of restructuring the form to make submitting the required information easier. However, I also spoke with several lawyers from our legal team and there is no getting around the parental consent form (though perhaps the process can still be made easier, I will ask).

Legal says:

Minors aren’t considered to have the appropriate legal capacity to enter into binding contracts. Their parent/guardian signs a consent, binding the minor to the contractual terms. In addition to the legal capacity issue, there are also additional data privacy obligations and risks related to processing of minors’ data.

It is possible we are complying with additional laws due to Dassault Systèmes, the parent company of SOLIDWORKS, being a European company. I apologize for the inconvenience.
